Lung on chip
Pulmonary diseases are reported to be the fifth most common cause of death globally. Several new interventions are tried to facilitate the treatment of pulmonary diseases.
Huh et al. from Wyss Institute of Harvard University were the pioneers in developing lung on a chip model [58]. In 2015, Huh and co-workers prepared an architecture and dynamic microenvironment surrogate to alveolar–capillary unit of the living human lung (as shown in theFig. 3). The system was then used to conduct nano-toxicological study in which production of intracellular reactive oxygen species (ROS) in response to alveolar exposure to nanoparticles was examined. It was also used to model pulmonary edema in human lungs [24].
